hints_latex:
Again compare the ODE with

\begin{align*}
P(x) y'' + Q(x) y' + R(x) y = 0.
\end{align*} We see that $P(x) = 2 x^2$,
$Q(x) = 3x + x^2$ and $R(x) = -1$. Now,

\begin{align*}
\lim_{x \to 0} x \frac{Q(x)}{P(x)} = \lim_{x \to 0} x \frac{3 x + x^2}{2 x^2} = \lim_{x \to 0} (\frac{3}{2} + \frac{1}{2} x) \;\; \text{is finite}
\end{align*}
and

\begin{align*}
\lim_{x \to 0} x^2 \frac{R(x)}{P(x)} = \lim_{x \to 0} x^2 \frac{-1}{2 x^2} = - \frac{1}{2} \;\; \text{is finite} .
\end{align*}
Therefore, $x = 0$ is a regular singular point.

Should we consider series solutions of the form

\begin{align*}
y(x) = \sum_{n = 0}^\infty a_n x^n \;\; \text{or} \;\; y(x) = \sum_{n = 0}^\infty a_n x^{n+r} ?
\end{align*}

sols_latex:
Following the comments in the hints, we see that $x = 0$ is a regular
singular point. Therefore, we should look for series solutions of the
form

\begin{align*}
y = \sum_{n = 0}^\infty a_n x^{n+r} .
\end{align*} We have that

\begin{align*}
y = \sum_{n = 0}^\infty a_n x^{n+r}, \; y' = \sum_{{\color{red} n = 0}}^\infty a_n (n+r) x^{n+r-1}, \; y'' = \sum_{{\color{red} n = 0}}^\infty a_n (n+r) (n+r-1)x^{n+r-2}  .
\end{align*}
(Please note that the both of the sums for $y'$ and $y''$ start at
$n=0$.)

Substitute these into the ODE

\begin{align*}
2 x^2 y'' + (3x + x^2) y' - y = 0,
\end{align*} we get that

\begin{align*}
\sum_{n = 0}^\infty 2 a_n (n+r)(n+r-1) x^{n+r} 
           +  \sum_{n = 0}^\infty 3 a_n (n+r) x^{n+r}
           {\color{blue} +  \sum_{n = 0}^\infty a_n (n+r) x^{n+r+1}}           + \sum_{n = 0}^\infty a_n x^{n+r} = 0.
\end{align*} We should shift the
index $n$ of ${\color{blue}  \sum_{n = 0}^\infty a_n (n+r)x^{n+r+1}}$
so the order of $x$ matches with the other terms. To do so, we should
replace every $n$ with $n-1$. Then

\begin{align*}
{\color{blue}  \sum_{n = 0}^\infty a_n (n+r) x^{n+r+1} } = \sum_{  n = {\color{red}1} }^\infty a_{  n {\color{red}-1} } (n+r {\color{red} -1} ) x^{ {\color{red} n+r}}  .
\end{align*}
Then we have

\begin{align*}
\sum_{n = 0}^\infty 2 a_n (n+r)(n+r-1) x^{n+r} 
           +  \sum_{n = 0}^\infty 3 a_n (n+r) x^{n+r}
           {\color{red} +  \sum_{n = 1}^\infty a_{n-1} (n+r-1) x^{n+r}}           + \sum_{n = 0}^\infty a_n x^{n+r} = 0
\end{align*} which, after
separating the $n = 0$ terms, can be rewritten as

\begin{align*}
[2 a_0 r(r-1) + 3 a_0 r - a_0] \; x^r
+ \sum_{n = 1}^\infty \; {\color{OliveGreen} [2 a_n (n+r)(n+r-1) + 3 a_n (n+r) + a_{n-1} (n+r-1) + a_n]} \;x^{n+r} 
= 0.
\end{align*}

Look at the above equation, because the right hand side is 0, the
coefficient of the $x^r$ term must be 0 as well. Hence,

\begin{align*}
[2 a_0 r(r-1) + 3 a_0 r - a_0] = a_0 (2r(r-1) + 3 r - 1) = 0. \,
\end{align*}
Now, if $a_0 = 0$, then all the subsequent $a_n$ will be zero as well
and we only get the trivial solution $y =0$. (Why? You can verify that
yourself after we finish the question. Set $a_0 = 0$ and you will see
the other terms will be forced to be 0 by the recursion relation.) In
other words, we must have

\begin{align*}
2r(r-1) + 3 r - 1 = 2r^2 + r - 1 = (2r-1) (r+1) = 0  \,
\end{align*} giving us
two roots $r = \frac{1}{2}$ and $r = -1 \,$. (Note: In the above,
$2r(r-1) + 3 r - 1 = 0$ is known as the indicial equation.)

By the same reason as $[2 a_0 r(r-1) + 3 a_0 r - a_0] = 0$, we have that

\begin{align*}
{\color{OliveGreen} [2 a_n (n+r)(n+r-1) + 3 a_n (n+r) + a_{n-1} (n+r-1) + a_n]} = 0 \;\; \text{foreach} \;\; n \geq 1. \,
\end{align*}

If we Isolate $a_{n}$, we get the recurrence relation

\begin{align*}
a_n = \frac{-(n+r-1) a_{n-1}}{2(n+r)(n+r-1) + 3(n+r) -1} \;\; \text{for} \;\; n \geq 1 .
\end{align*}

After simplifying and factoring the expression in the denominator, the
above expression can be rewritten as

\begin{align*}
a_n = \frac{-(n+r-1) a_{n-1}}{2(n+r)^2 + (n+r) -1} = \frac{-(n+r-1) a_{n-1}}{(2(n+r) -1)((n+r)+1)}
\end{align*}
which may be easier to do calculations with.

Now recall that from the indicial equation, we found $r = \frac{1}{2}$
and $r = -1 \,$.

In the case $r = -1 \,$,
$y = \sum_{n =0}^\infty a_n x^{n-1} = a_0 x^{-1} + a_1 + a_2 x + \cdots$.

Note that the above equation does not satisfy
$\lim_{x \to 0^+} y(x) = 0$ due to the $a_0 x^{-1}$ term, so the
expression corresponding to $r = -1$ is not what the question is asking
for.

In the case $r = \frac{1}{2}$ ,
$y = \sum_{n =0}^\infty a_n x^{n+\frac{1}{2}} = a_0 x^{\frac{1}{2}} + a_1 x^{\frac{3}{2}} + a_2 x^{\frac{5}{2}} + \cdots$.

Note that the above equation satisfies $\lim_{x \to 0^+} y(x) = 0$. In
other words, this is the one the question is asking for.

It remains to find $a_1$ and $a_2$ in terms of $a_0$. To find $a_1$,
substitue $n = 1 \,$ and $r = \frac{1}{2}$ into the recurrence relation.
We get that

\begin{align*}
a_1 = \frac{-(1 + \frac{1}{2} - 1) a_0}{(2(1+\frac{1}{2})-1)(1+\frac{1}{2}+1)} = \frac{-1}{10} a_0 .
\end{align*}

To find $a_2$, substitue $n = 2 \,$ and $r = \frac{1}{2}$ into the
recurrence relation. We get that

\begin{align*}
a_2 = \frac{-(2 + \frac{1}{2} - 1) a_1}{(2(2+\frac{1}{2})-1)(2 +\frac{1}{2}+1)} = \frac{-3}{28} a_1 = \frac{-3}{28} (\frac{-1}{10} a_0) = \frac{3}{280} a_0 .
\end{align*}

Therefore, we have

\begin{align*}
y(x) = a_0 x^{\frac{1}{2}} + a_1 x^{\frac{3}{2}} + a_2 x^{\frac{5}{2}} + \cdots= a_0 x^{\frac{1}{2}} - \frac{1}{10} a_0 x^{\frac{3}{2}} + \frac{3}{280} a_0 x^{\frac{5}{2}} + \cdots
\end{align*}

statement_latex:
For the ordinary differential equation

\begin{align*}
2 x^2 y'' + (3x + x^2) y' - y = 0 , \,
\end{align*}

find the first 3 terms of a non-zero series solution about $x = 0$
satisfying

\begin{align*}
\lim_{x \to 0^+} y(x) = 0.
\end{align*}
